n - both essential). \r\n\r\njQuery\r\nOn to jQuery: once again, blow through Code Academy\'s jQuery curriculum. Build 2-3 games with JavaScript and jQuery (TicTacToe, Snake, etc.). jQuery\'s API documentation is fantastic and will be your reference. With jQuery, in the beginning, you just need an understanding of selectors (same as CSS) and a few utility methods that you\'ll be using all the time. \r\n\r\n\r\nThe essentials:\r\n\r\n1\r\n2\r\n3\r\n4\r\n5\r\n6\r\naddClass()\r\nremoveClass()\r\nhtml()\r\nappend()\r\nremove()\r\non()\r\n\r\n\r\nOver time, you\'ll collect more and more jQuery methods. Pay particular attention to on() as it is how you\'ll bind all your event listeners and handlers (callbacks).\r\n\r\nNode\r\nLastly, move to node. If you\'ve done your work well learning JavaScript and using JS + jQuery to build some reasonably large client-side projects, then you\'ll be well-prepared to learn node. You\'ll now have to layer on a basic understanding of servers and node\'s asynchronous I/O. Tack on jQuery\'s $.ajax() method for client-server communication and you\'ll have a full-stack app in no time. You can look up tutorials but don\'t shirk reading node.js documentation.\r\n\r\nCoffeeScript\r\nP.S. As a Python programmer, you\'re a fan of clean, good-looking, straightforward code. JavaScript has none of those things out of the box. First, heed Crockford\'s advice in JavaScript: The Good Parts and avoid large chunks of the language. Stick to the good parts (which are really good). And if you\'d like (and I highly recommend you do), pick up CoffeeScript. CoffeeScript is a language that compiles to JavaScript and is beautiful. It is heavily influenced by Python and Ruby, and generally only includes the good parts of JavaScript (plus a bunch of CoffeeScript additions, all of which are just great).','Eloquent Javascript Week Long Challenge','','draft','open','open','','','','','2014-08-02 17:38:44','2014-08-02 17:38:44','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?p=2863',