erm gave clarity to why “full-stack developers” were critical to build an early startup team. You can’t afford to have a VP of Engineering whose whole job is to manage the engineering team because you don’t have an engineering team. You can’t afford to have a DBA just to manage the database, because your database doesn’t have enough data. At the same time, every week you need a few hours of DBA, a few hours of “VP-ing,” a few hours of architecture design, a few hours of HTML/CSS coding, a few hours of API integration, etc. The solution startups found is to have full-stack developers.[/blockquote]\r\n\r\nIn the same way, you can\'t have a guy who solely books meetings. Or a person whose sole job is to create email campaigns. When you\'re just getting off the ground, there\'s a definite need for a hustler who can hit all major pain points in the organization, and create value as soon as possible.\r\n\r\nThat also explains why startups are some of the best training grounds on the planet-- you\'re forced into a role where you must learn to keep up and contribute. And why not? Google is your friend, and the digital industry is especially keen on sharing and spreading wisdom.\r\n\r\nStep aside MBAs, make way for the full stack marketer.','Step Aside MBAs, Make Way for the Full Stack Marketer','','inherit','open','open','','2858-revision-v1','','','2014-08-12 23:13:46','2014-08-12 23:13:46','',2858,'http://shipordeliver.com/2858-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(2880,1,'2014-08-13 22:08:15','2014-08-13 22:08:15','[dropcap custom_class=\"normal\"]Please note that what I\'m about to say only applies to startups. People who have a Master in Business Administration degree from an elite school are generally folks who\'ve gone to amazing undergraduate institutions, worked at some top-notch companies and performed well, and scored high enough on the grueling GMAT to land themselves in a six-figure job. In no way am I discrediting MBA-holders-- as a matter of fact, I may get an MB