tstrap, front-end development indeed looks like a fun place to be right now.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nI had previously been a front-end developer at an old firm. I had been hired after a few small projects, and was ready to butt heads with fellow developers. I went in there thinking that my little knowledge of HTML and CSS would suffice-- after all, the front-end is just the visuals, right?\r\n\r\nI was completely blindsided. The HTML and CSS skills I had picked up during my independent study did not prepare me for the new world of web that we had entered in. Yes, I could convert a PSD to a standard HTML boilerplate template, and of course, I was able to manipulate Wordpress and Magento themes. However, I knew next-to-nothing about the emerging world of Javascript libraries going in, and even less about the ways it connected with functionality.\r\n\r\nI found myself googling such terms as \"What is a parallax effect?\" and \"Jquery tutorial\" quite often. I was able to do a semi-decent job after a while, but little did I know how truly lost I was.\r\n\r\nThe truth of the matter is, front-end development is now less about web design and more about programming. Anyone can design something pretty, but look at the stylishness and flexibility of features on <a title=\"CSS Design Awards\" href=\"http://www.cssdesignawards.com\" target=\"_blank\">CSSDA</a> and tell me how much of that is truly just visual. The dynamic elements, the frameworks, and the truly kick-ass things you can do within a browser are now <a title=\"Flat vs. Realism\" href=\"http://www.flatvsrealism.com\" target=\"_blank\">bordering on absurd</a>.\r\n\r\nAlthough I now focus more on project management than pure development, I still think that everyone ought to learn HTML5, CSS3, and Javascript. Here\'s some reasons why:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Everyone needs a web presence... why should anyone else build JacobZhang.net?</li>\r\n	<li>It gives a fantastic introduction to more complex uses of programming.</li>\r\n	<li>It pretty much forces you to learn about colors, hues, opacity, and some Photoshop.</li>\r\n	<li>It will force you to understand how the web really works, and given that everyone\'s jumping on the net, I\'d say that\'s pretty useful.</li>\r\n	<li>Front-end developers at startups are now making a killing. These skills are clearly valuable. While everyone won\'t become a developer, there will always be a demand.</li>\r\n	<li>It\'s really fun. It makes you feel like an artist.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\nI\'m eager to get back into front-end development as a hobby, and am currently masterminding a plan of action to 1) learn the skills and 2) create a jaw-dropping portfolio. Look out for it soon!','Re-learning and Mastering the Front-End','','publish','open','open','','re-learning-and-mastering-the-front-end','','','2015-03-10 02:33:24','2015-03-10 02:33:24','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?p=2881',0,'post','',0),(2882,1,'2014-08-13 22:31:04','2014-08-13 22:31:04','<a title=\"The Hottest Job Around\" href=\"http://www.ozy.com/fast-forward/the-hottest-job-around-front-end-developers/30386.article\" target=\"_blank\">This article</a> claims that front-end development is currently the hottest job around. <a title=\"High Paying Jobs of the Future\" href=\"http://www.forbes.com/sites/learnvest/2013/09/16/6-high-paying-jobs-of-the-future/2/\" target=\"_blank\">A separate article</a> calls front-end engineers \"a super-critical position\", with a significant impact on the user experience. I think that we can all agree that with the outburst of Web 2.0 apps, and the rapid innovation (and vitality) of new web technologies like AngularJS and Twitter Bootstrap, front-end development indeed looks like a fun place to be right now.\r\n\r\nI had previously been a front-end developer at an old firm. I had been hired after a few small projects, and was ready to butt heads with fellow developers. I went in there thinking that my little knowledge of HTML and CSS would suffice-- after all, the front