aft','open','open','','','','','2014-10-07 16:45:43','2014-10-07 16:45:43','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?p=2931',0,'post','',0),(2932,1,'2014-10-07 16:45:43','2014-10-07 16:45:43','http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/news/2006-08-30-dot-fun_x.htm\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nhttp://www.forbes.com/sites/victoriabarret/2012/11/20/a-mess-of-family-dynamics-alleged-in-lawsuit-against-silicon-valley-entrepreneur-and-color-founder-bill-nguyen/','Passion in Startups','','inherit','open','open','','2931-revision-v1','','','2014-10-07 16:45:43','2014-10-07 16:45:43','',2931,'http://shipordeliver.com/2931-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(2933,1,'2014-10-07 17:04:18','0000-00-00 00:00:00','http://www.fastcompany.com/1784823/bill-nguyen-the-boy-in-the-bubble','Abundance','','draft','open','open','','','','','2014-10-07 17:04:18','2014-10-07 17:04:18','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?p=2933',0,'post','',0),(2934,1,'2014-10-07 17:04:18','2014-10-07 17:04:18','http://www.fastcompany.com/1784823/bill-nguyen-the-boy-in-the-bubble','Abundance','','inherit','open','open','','2933-revision-v1','','','2014-10-07 17:04:18','2014-10-07 17:04:18','',2933,'http://shipordeliver.com/2933-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(2936,1,'2015-02-26 13:14:58','2015-02-26 13:14:58','I\'ve been on a bit of a learning spree lately-- a man on a mission to absorb all potentially useful knowledge. My mind\'s been acting like a sponge, hopefully retaining everything I\'ve been reading, watching, and studying. It\'s a shame that this phenomenon isn\'t a more permanent thing; it seems to come in waves. After a trigger of sorts, I\'ll find myself experiencing bliss upon metaphorically digging a hole in several books, but this quickly comes to a peak and dissolves into complacency and boredom quickly.\r\n\r\nWhat I\'ve noticed, however, is that despite the duration, I retain a considerable amount more. I am actively engaged in the learning process without realizing it, and it\'s primarily because I\'m having a good time. As a project manager, I\'ve tried to pick up and read through hoards of books on project management, but I cannot finish them as I would a mystery novel. They\'re written in such a dry, factual manner-- reminiscent of college textbooks-- but that\'s not the reason they bore me.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nThe first reason is because as a practicing project manager, I understand there\'s such a disconnect between the advice dispensed by gurus and actual application. Real project management is less about constraints, dependencies, and charts than it is clear written and verbal communication and people skills. The second reason, and the primary reason I write this post, is that because of reason one, I don\'t have a intrinsic purpose for reading it. As a practicing project manager, I am gaining hands-on experience that counts. I could pretend like it matters how I format my project plans, or the methods of prioritization of tasks, but having worked in the role for so long, I know what truly matters.\r\n\r\nTo extend my point, I know for sure I would thus be much more engaged, and happy, to take a public speaking course or read a book on emotional intelligence. Those things matter to me, on a deep, intrinsic level. Our brains are smart enough to filter through what matters and what doesn\'t, and try to trick it as we may (who actually does every single reading assignment in college?), our engagement and interest levels will always shine through in our level of joy while learning.\r\n\r\nSo here comes the problem with traditional academia, and this comes as no insult to any specific school but as a criticism of all forms of schooling worldwide: it\'s an open fact that a large portion of students are bored out of their minds a good amount of the time they are in school. Based on my observation above, this becomes problematic, being that they are essentially wasting their time on knowledge and courses they don\'t care about and will probably never use. This is why many students do much better in college, or graduate school, when they get to choose an area of interest instead of being forced to sit through a \"comprehensive\" curriculum.\r\n\r\nLiberal arts proponents will argue that a wide-ranging curriculum exposes students to new ideas and interests. I agree with the intention-- as Steve Jobs once said, and I paraphrase, innovation comes from people having different experiences in life and contributing their uniqueness. However, those experiences should come in the form of dull books. They should be lived and breathed.\r\n\r\nI don\'t have a fix for the system in place, but it is certainly telling that vocational schools, online courses, and development bootcamps are gaining tons of traction. An investment in one of those will likely go considerably farther than a traditional $160k liberal arts degree.','The Joy of Constant Learning and My Beef with Academia','','publish','open','open','','the-joy-of-constant-learning-and-my-beef-with-academia','','','2015-04-09 03:59:35','2015-04-09 03:59:35','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?p=2936',0,'post','',0),(2937,1,'2014-11-15 04:05:44','2014-11-15 04:05:44','I\'ve been on a bit of a learning spree lately-- a man on a mission to absorb all potentially useful knowledge. My mind\'s been acting like a sponge, hopefully retaining everything I\'ve been reading, watching, and studying. It\'s a shame that this phenomenon isn\'t a more permanent thing; it seems to come in waves. After a trigger of sorts, I\'ll find myself experiencing bliss upon metaphorically digging a hole in a several books, engulfed by','The Joy of Constant Learning','','inherit','open','open','','2936-revision-v1','','','2014-11-15 04:05:44','2014-11-15 04:05:44','',2936,'http://shipordeliver.com/2936-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(2940,1,'2015-02-24 21:29:49','2015-02-24 21:29:49','','Portfolio','','inherit','open','open','','778-revision-v1','','','2015-02-24 21:29:49','2015-02-24 21:29:49','',778,'http://shipordeliver.com/778-re