r a trigger of sorts, I\'ll find myself experiencing bliss upon metaphorically digging a hole in several books, but this quickly comes to a peak and dissolves into complacency and boredom quickly.\r\n\r\nWhat I\'ve noticed, however, is that despite the duration, I retain a considerable amount more. I am actively engaged in the learning process without realizing it, and it\'s primarily because I\'m having a good time. As a project manager, I\'ve tried to pick up and read through hoards of books on project management, but I cannot finish them as I would a mystery novel. They\'re written in such a dry, factual manner-- reminiscent of college textbooks-- but that\'s not the reason they bore me.\r\n\r\nThe first reason is because as a practicing project manager, I understand there\'s such a disconnect between the advice dispensed by gurus and actual application. Real project management is less about constraints, dependencies, and charts than it is clear written and verbal communication and people skills.\r\n\r\nThe second reason, and the primary reason I write this post, is that because of reason one, I don\'t have a intrinsic purpose for reading it. As a practicing project manager, I am gaining hands-on experience that counts. I could pretend like it matters how I format my project plans, or the methods of prioritization of tasks, but having worked in the role for so long, I know what truly matters.\r\n\r\nTo extend my point, I know for sure I would thus be much more engaged, and happy, to take a public speaking course or read a book on emotional intelligence. Those things matter to me, on a deep, intrinsic level. Our brains our smart enough to filter through what matters and what doesn\'t, and try to trick it as we may (who actually does every single reading assignment in college?), our engagement and interest levels will always shine through in our level of joy while learning.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','The Joy of Constant Learning and My Beef with Academia','','inherit','open',