o be services. Amazon is an example of a company using monolithic software that converted to a service-oriented architecture.</li><br>\r\n	<li>SaaS infrastructure requires 1) communication, 2) scalability, and 3) dependability. Clusters (commodity computers connected by ethernet switches) proved to be scalable and cheap. Cloud computing offers computing, storage, and communication at pennies per hour with no premium to scale. Amazon\'s AWS model seems to have won out: even Amazon.com is a client of Amazon Web Services.</li><br>\r\n	<li>In legacy code, 60% of costs goes to adding features in software maintenance and 17% goes to fixing bugs. Every single company wants programmers who can deal with undocumented legacy code.</li><br>\r\n	<li>Software quality is defined as satisfying the customers\' needs and being easy for developers to debug and enhance. Verification means: did you meet the specification? Validation means: does the specification reflect what the client actually wants?\r\n	<ul><li>A unit test checks if a single method does what was expected.</li>\r\n	<li>A module or functional test checks across individual units.</li>\r\n	<li>An integration test ensures that interfaces between units have consistent assumptions and communicate correctly.</li></ul></li>\r\n</ul>','BerkeleyX: Engineering SaaS, Wk 1, Intro to SWE Notes','','draft','open','open','','berkeleyx-engineering-saas-wk-1-intro-to-swe-notes','','','2015-08-03 02:50:28','2015-08-03 02:50:28','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?page_id=3008',0,'page','',0),(3009,1,'2015-03-15 22:00:09','2015-03-15 22:00:09','Here are my notes from week 1 of of BerkeleyX\'s edX offering, <a href=\"https://courses.edx.org/courses/BerkeleyX/CS-CS169.1x/3T2014/courseware/\" target=\"_blank\">Engineering Software as a Service</a>:\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Software engineering is constantly ranked as one of the best professions, but over 60 years of history says that human beings are still really bad at it.</li>\r\n	<li>Software