ct what the client actually wants?\r\n	<ul><li>A unit test checks if a single method does what was expected.</li>\r\n	<li>A module or functional test checks across individual units.</li>\r\n	<li>An integration test ensures that interfaces between units have consistent assumptions and communicate correctly.</li></ul></li>\r\n</ul>','BerkeleyX: Engineering SaaS, Wk 1, Intro to SWE & Ruby Intro Notes','','inherit','open','open','','3013-revision-v1','','','2015-03-15 22:22:21','2015-03-15 22:22:21','',3013,'http://shipordeliver.com/3013-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3018,1,'2015-03-15 22:29:59','2015-03-15 22:29:59','These are notes that I have taken as I went through Tealeaf Academy\'s book,  <a title=\"Introduction to Git and Github\" href=\"http://www.gotealeaf.com/books/git/read/introduction\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Introduction to Git and Github</em></a>, provided for free as part of the online Ruby curriculum. I practiced using Nitrous.io on my Windows machine. I found it to be quite a helpful refresher, as I haven\'t used Git regularly or professionally in over a year.\r\n\r\n<strong>Git/Github Basics</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Git and Github focuses on the people aspect of programming, it helps give closure to our efforts and share it with others.</li>\r\n	<li>Source Control Management is the process developers use to iterate on their codebases. They keep a historical record of the files in the codebase and also manage workflows, enabling large numbers of people to work on large projects simultaneously.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!--more-->\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Git has become popular because it is distributed, which makes projects resilient to a lone point of failure. It is a distributed version control system, where there is no main central repository, and developers work with local repos instead. Most teams will not push commits directly to each other, but rather through a main repository-- usually hosted on Github.com</li>\r\n	<li>FOSS stands for Free and Open Source Software, and there are thousands of open source projects out there with millions of programmers working on them.</li>\r\n	<li>Github, built on git, connected people and code from around the globe and created an eco-system/interface for them.</li>\r\n	<li>Git comes in GUI form and command line. All of the commands possible in the GUI are relayed to the underlying command line in application.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Working Locally</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>.md files stand for files in the markdown format, which is readable as plain text and renders well on github.com</li>\r\n	<li>Initializing a directory with \"git init\" adds a .git directory to the folder, but is conceptually thought of as turning that aforementioned directory into a git repository. To switch it back to a normal folder, simply delete the .git folder.</li>\r\n	<li>There are 3 places on your system where git configuration is kept: /etc/gitconfig, ~/.gitconfig, and /.git/config.</li>\r\n	<li>The .gitignore file lives in the repository\'s directory and is a list what users do not want shown in their repositories.</li>\r\n	<li>You can think of a \"commit\" as a way to \"logically group a bundle of various changes together\". Adding files to the commit tells git which should be included. The -m flag allows developers to add a message to the commit.</li>\r\n	<li>\"git log\" gives a history of commits. Good commit hygiene is expected on most teams to ensure efficiency.</li>\r\n	<li>Branching is a maintaining a copy of the codebase separately from the main version, and allows experimentation and testing without affecting the main codebase. If experimentation goes well, developers can merge commits from the separate branch to the master branch if desired.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Remote Repositories</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A remote repository can be used for a variety of reasons, including back-up and collaboration. Github.com often hosts the centralized repositories, acting as the single source of truth for the codebase. Most developers use the name <strong>origin</strong> for the central repo.</li>\r\n	<li>If you are using a Nitrous remote box, as I am, you may need to authenticate with a Publickey. Nitrous makes it easy-- <a href=\"http://help.nitrous.io/github-add-key/\" target=\"_blank\">click here</a> for instructions.</li>\r\n	<li>The \"git clone\" makes an exact clone of the existing remote repo and copies it to your local machine. It\'s primarily used when working on new projects or pulling down open source ones.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;','Git Repository and Github Notes','','inherit','open','open','','2992-revision-v1','','','2015-03-15 22:29:59','2015-03-15 22:29:59','',2992,'http://shipordeliver.com/2992-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3021,1,'2015-03-15 22:34:10','2015-03-15 22:34:10','&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Tealeaf Academy:</b>\r\n\r\nBuild Robust and Production Quality Applications\r\n\r\nRapid Prototyping with Ruby on Rails\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>BerkeleyX: </b>\r\n\r\nEngineering Software as a Service Part 1\r\n\r\nEngineering Software as a Service Part 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>CodeAcademy</b>\r\n\r\nPython track\r\n\r\nJavascript track','My Curriculum','','inherit','open','open','','3001-revision-v1','','','2015-03-15 22:34:10','2015-03-15 22:34:10','',3001,'http://shipordeliver.com/3001-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3023,1,'2015-03-15 22:36:54','2015-03-15 22:36:54','','Articles and Posts','','publish','open','open','','articles-and-posts','','','2016-01-01 17:14:43','2016-01-01 17:14:43','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?p=3023',2,'nav_menu_item','',0),(3025,1,'2015-03-15 22:38:24','2015-03-15 22:38:24','[parallax photourl=\"http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/aboutmepic.jpg\" verticaloffset=\"280\" title=\"My name is Buzz\" text=\"Below you will find, a couple of words about me\" textmargin=\"100\" overlaycolor=\"#222\" overlayopacity=\"0.75\"][/parallax]\r\n\r\n[widerow customclass=\"white\"]\r\n\r\n[row_fluid]\r\n\r\n[span4]\r\n[dro