ural design, 3) implementation &amp; integration, 4) verification, and 5) operation and maintenance. Usually when customers see it, they will want changes to the software product, and will realize the right way to do it.</li>\r\n	<li>The spiral lifecycle was next, with a circular iterations. However, they could take 6 to 24 month long, and there\'s often too many rules to follow with a high cost.</li>\r\n	<li>RUP had 4 phases: 1) inception, 2) elaboration, 3) construction, and 4) transition. Unfortunately, tools are expensive and are only good for medium to large sizes.</li>\r\n	<li>To avoid needing a strong project manager or simply \"hacking\", the Agile Manifesto (2001) was written. XP version involves extremely short iterations, simplicity, writing test code prematurely, and programming in pairs. The Agile lifecycle is best for SaaS, but not so much for NASA or code subject to regulations.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Introduction to Ruby</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n</ul>','BerkeleyX: Engineering SaaS, Wk 1, Agile & Ruby Intro Notes','','inherit','open','open','','3028-revision-v1','','','2015-03-16 13:57:20','2015-03-16 13:57:20','',3028,'http://shipordeliver.com/3028-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3032,1,'2015-03-16 14:32:08','2015-03-16 14:32:08','This is the curriculum that I set for myself early on, and constantly iterating on, in my goal to learn software engineering. I believe it\'s a skill that everyone should learn, not just because computers and technology is paving the future for society, but also because it forces one to think in a logical manner. Watch the below video to see my source of inspiration for learning how to code:\r\n\r\n<iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/pvAsqPbz9Ro\" width=\"100%\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe>\r\n\r\n<b>Tealeaf Academy:</b>\r\n\r\nBuild Robust and Production Quality Applications\r\n\r\nRapid Prototyping with Ruby on Rails\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>May 2015 - July 2015</h2>\r\n<b>BerkeleyX: </b>\r\n\r\nEngineering Software as a Service Part 1\r\n\r\nEngineering Software as a Service Part 1\r\n<h2>March 2015 - April 2015</h2>\r\nhttps://class.coursera.org/webapplications-003\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>November 2014 - February 2015</h2>\r\nBuild Your Own Social Network Series + Bootstrap Hacking\r\n\r\nA 43-part video series culminating in my portfolio piece here:\r\n<h2>2012 - 2014</h2>\r\n<b>CodeAcademy</b>\r\n\r\nPython track\r\n\r\nJavascript track','My Curriculum','','inherit','open','open','','3001-revision-v1','','','2015-03-16 14:32:08','2015-03-16 14:32:08','',3001,'http://shipordeliver.com/3001-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3033,1,'2015-03-16 18:18:52','2015-03-16 18:18:52','<p>In going through BerkeleyX\'s Software as a Service MOOC, I realized that I still needed a refresher to truly understand the overall architecture of Ruby and Ruby on Rails. I found this CourseEra class, <a href=\"https://www.coursera.org/course/webapplications\" title=\"Web Application Architectures\" target=\"_blank\">Web Application Architectures</a>, that seems to be a beginner-intermediate level course to provide a basic overview of the framework. I\'m going to be taking this before finishing the SaaS MOOC to gain more confidence and round out the edges on web apps. Here are my notes from the first module:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Pace of innovation in computing has been remarkable - first electronic computer was started in 1945. Initial usage was for military and business purposes.</li>\r\n	<li>TCP/IP came through in 1980 which paved the way for the World Wide Web., and eventually Amazon, Google, and Facebook.</li><!--more-->\r\n	<li>Ajax, EC2, and HTML5-- more recent trends-- have paved the way for internet interactivity. We\'re currently in the Web 3.0 phase (machine-facilitated understanding of information; \"the intelligent web\"). Web 2.0 involved interactivity, social networking, media sharing, etc.</li>\r\n	<li>Modern web application architectures have been refined over time.</li>\r\n	<li>Most basic model is the client-server architecture: the server listens for the request and the client component issues the request.</li>\r\n	<li>Most basic model is the client-server architecture: the server listens for the request and the client component issues the request. In our case, the \"network\" is the Internet and we access it via HTTP. Advantages include ubiquity of using a web browser as a client, cross-platform compatibility, and easy updates. Disadvantages include number of moving parts and privacy.</li>\r\n	<li>Application Architectures:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Web 1.0 was primarily fetching static web pages - there was a lack of interactivity. Applications became richer, the \"browser wars\" happened, and developers needed to \"save states\".</li>\r\n	<li>Web 2.0 and 3.0 - server-side functionality is partitioned more intelligently. Web 2.0 allows for more read-write online. Web 3.0 is approaching a billion indexed webpages with much more interactivity.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>A design pattern is an abstract template that can be applied over and over again to solve specific design problems. They also provide a way to communicate parts of a design among software engineers.</li>\r\n	<li>The n-tier architecture is based on breaking a system into different pieces that can be separated and provides a specific functionality. A print server is an example of a 2-tier architectural pattern. Advantages are that it provides a means for managing the complexity of the design, tiers can be upgraded or replaced independently, and it provides a balance between innovation and standardization.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A modern web application is usually 3-tier: 1) A presentation tier, 2) application tier, and a 3) database tier. The presentation tier can be broken down into client tier and presentation logic tier. The application tier is often broken down into the business logic tier and data access tier (which lets us switch out the DB).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','Web Application Architectures Introduction and Background','','private','open','open','','web-application-architectures-introduction-and-background','','','2015-08-02 15:34:49','2015-08-02 15:34:49','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?p=3033',0,'post','',0),(3034,1,'2015-03-16 18:08:05','2015-03-16 18:08:05','<ul>\r\n	<li>Pace of innovation in computing has been remarkable - first electronic computer was started in 1945. Initial usage was for military and business purposes.</li>\r\n	<li>TCP/IP came through in 1980 which paved the way for the World Wide Web., and eventually Amazon, Google, and Facebook.</li>\r\n	<li>Ajax, EC2, and HTML5-- more recent trends-- have paved the way for internet interactivity. We\'re currently in the Web 3.0 phase (machine-facilitated understanding of information; \"the intelligent web\"). Web 2.0 involved interactivity, social networking, media sharing, etc.</li>\r\n	<li>Modern web application architectures have been refined over time.</li>\r\n	<li>Most basic model is the client-server architecture: the server listens for the request and the client component issues the request.</li>\r\n	<li>Most basic model is the client-server architecture: the server listens for the request and the client component issues the request. In our case, the \"network\" is the Internet and we access it via HTTP. Advantages include ubiquity of using a web browser as a client, cross-platform compatibility, and easy updates. Disadvantages include number of moving parts and privacy.</li>\r\n	<li>Application Architectures:\r\n	<ul><li>Web 1.0 was primarily fetching static web pages - there was a lack of interactivity. Applications became richer, the \"browser wars\" happened, and developers needed to \"save states\".</li>\r\n<li>Web 2.0 and 3.0 - server-side functionality is partitioned more intelligently. Web 2.0 allows for more read-write online. Web 3.0 is approaching a billion indexed webpages with much more interactivity.</li