RAKE, Webrick, etc.</li>\n	<li>The framework is built around the Model-View-Controller pattern.</li>\n	<li>Criticisms include a lack of scalability (there was a high-profile failure at Twitter) and that it\'s \"magic\" and too automatic. Professor thinks it\'s a part of the natural progression of programming: from Bits to Assembly to HLL to OOP to frameworks.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>To create a new app, type \"$ rails new my_app\" in command line and then \"$ rails server\" to start the web server, and view it at http://localhost:3000.</li>\n	<li>Always run \"bundle install\" as the gems necessary are included in the application.</li>\n	<li>Architecture:\n<ul>\n	<li>/app - Models, Views and Controllers code</li>\n	<li>/bin - Helper scripts (bundle, rails, rake)</li>\n	<li>/config - App, database & route configuration</li>\n	<li>/db - Database schema and migrations</li>\n	<li>/Gemfile - Specify the required gems</li>\n	<li>/log - Application logging directory</li>\n	<li>/public - Webroot of the application</li>\n	<li>/tests - Tests - Agile development</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>Let\'s build a blog, with 2 users: administrator and author. We will use scaffolding and generators to create some of the components.</li>\n	<li>\"$ rake routes\" gives you a list of URLs affiliated with the app.</li>\n	<li><strong>Rails Philosophy</strong> - Convention over Configuration, Don\'t Repeat Yourself (DRY), and Agile Development (iterative/incremental process).</li>\n	<li>DRY - Every piece of information should have a single, unambiguous, authoritative representation within a system.</li>\n	<li>Test-driven development (TDD) - build/develop tests first. Behavior-driven development (BDD) is a 2nd-gen agile approach and writes test cases in a natural language that anyone can read.</li>\n<li>Version control helps a project as it evolves. The need for managing software versions has existed for as long as there\'s been software. Locally, it\'s easy-- you just save a file to a different version. Teams need centralized version control servers.</li>\n	<li>Distributed version control requires no centralized repository, they check out the entire repository (team members can work simultaneously).</li>\n</ul>','Web Application Architectures: Ruby on Rails','','inherit','open','open','','3049-autosave-v1','','','2015-03-20 23:58:16','2015-03-20 23:58:16','',3049,'http://shipordeliver.com/3049-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3053,1,'2015-03-24 14:15:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','What I\'ve Learned from Software Autodidactism','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-03-24 14:15:01','2015-03-24 14:15:01','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?p=3053',0,'post','',0),(3054,1,'2015-03-24 14:15:01','2015-03-24 14:15:01','','What I\'ve Learned from Software Autodidactism','','inherit','open','open','','3053-revision-v1','','','2015-03-24 14:15:01','2015-03-24 14:15:01','',3053,'http://shipordeliver.com/3053-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3055,1,'2015-03-24 16:49:30','2015-03-24 16:49:30','Notes, as usual, from the awesome MOOC here. I attached some photos this time, as we\'re finally really diving into the working/programming component of the course.\r\n\r\n<strong>Relational Databases</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A relational database is used to store a collection of relations and involves storing \"records\" in tables.</li>\r\n	<li>The ID field is often referred to as \"the primary key\". One-to-many relationships can be fixed by NORMALIZING - creating two tables, and searching by the \"foreign key\" to parse for different values.</li>\r\n	<li>The structure/organization of the tables in a database can be called a schema and are captured by an entity-relationship model. MySQL Work bench is useful for visualization.</li><!--more-->\r\n	<li>A many to many relationship (between and addresses) can be done by utilizing a join table.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Databases in Rails</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>When the scaffold generator is run, Rails creates a database migration file. Rails uses SQLite.</li>\r\n	<li>To use another environment, use \"rails server -e production\" to use the production environment.</li>\r\n	<li>SQLite is not a production grade environment.</li>\r\n	<li>The database that rails will use in different environments is specified in db/database.yml</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>The Active Record Design Pattern</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The Active Record Design pattern was named by Martin Fowler. It saves data persistently.</li>\r\n	<li>Classes and objects associated with an Object Oriented language are not compatible with the structure of relational databses. It creates a \"Virtual object store\": object oriented classes get mapped to tables, objects get mapped to records, and attributes get mapped to record values. There is a Ruby module called ActiveRecord, built in Rails, that takes care of this and perform CRUD operations.</li>\r\n	<li>If you create a new class by inheriting ActiveRecord::Base, and call it Post, it is assumed that DB table exists and will automatically add member variables with the same names in the Post class.</li>\r\n	<li>The interactive Ruby shell (IRB) is an interpreter that is provided with Ruby, opened with command \"$ irb\".</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Associations</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The scaffold generator automatically sets up the SQLite database and connection, as well as the ORM.</li>\r\n	<li>However, the connections between the scaffolds themselves are not yet connected (posts and comments)-- use of the foreign key ASSOCATIONS (models like has_one, has_many, etc.) takes care of this. This is manipulated in the /models folder.</li>\r\n	<li>To manage the association in terms of URL, you need to nest the comments resources under posts.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<a href=\"http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/module3-2.png\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-3057\" src=\"http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/module3-2.png\" alt=\"module3-2\" width=\"833\" height=\"628\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Data Validation</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Data validation ensures that your application operates on clean and useful data (ex. formatting phone numbers). The most common web application security weakness is failure to validate client-side input, and can be solved by cleaning your input.</li>\r\n	<li>Checks include:</li>\r\n	<li>Client side - making sure HTML forms are filled out correctly (used to be in JS but HTML5 has more specific input types).</li>\r\n	<li>Server side:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>DB - these are checks after submission of the HTML for, but it is DB dependent.</li>\r\n	<li>Controller - want to keep logic in controller skinny.</li>\r\n	<li>Model level - checking things before it gets saved to the DB.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Callbacks are methods that get called at certain points in an ActiveRecord object\'s lifecycle.</li>\r\n	<li>Validations are a type of ActiveRecord callback that can be used to ensure valid data -- they are defined within models.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<a href=\"http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/module3-3.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-3058\" src=\"http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/module3-3.png\" alt=\"module3-3\" width=\"1347\" height=\"658\" /></a>','Web Application Architectures: Database Interactions','','private','open','open','','web-application-architectures-database-interactions','','','2015-08-02 15:34:49','2015-08-02 15:34:49','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?p=3055',0,'post','',0),(3056,1,'2015-03-24 16:42:51','2015-03-24 16:42:51','','module3-1','','inherit','open','open','','module3-1','','','2015-03-24 16:42:51','2015-03-24 16:42:51','',3055,'http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/module3-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(3057,1,'2015-03-24 16:42:57','2015-03-24 16:42:57','','module3-2','','inherit','open','open','','module3-2','','','2015-03-24 16:42:57','2015-03-24 16:42:57','',3055,'http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/modul