ctiveRecord callback that can be used to ensure valid data -- they are defined within models.</li>\r\n</ul>','Web Application Architectures: Database Interactions','','inherit','open','open','','3055-revision-v1','','','2015-03-24 16:46:13','2015-03-24 16:46:13','',3055,'http://shipordeliver.com/3055-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3060,1,'2015-03-24 16:48:59','2015-03-24 16:48:59','Notes, as usual, from the awesome MOOC here. I attached some photos this time, as we\'re finally really diving into the working/programming component of the course.\r\n\r\n<strong>Relational Databases</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A relational database is used to store a collection of relations and involves storing \"records\" in</li>\r\n	<li>tables.</li>\r\n	<li>The ID field is often referred to as \"the primary key\". One-to-many relationships can be fixed by NORMALIZING - creating two tables, and searching by the \"foreign key\" to parse for different values.</li>\r\n	<li>The structure/organization of the tables in a database can be called a schema and are captured by an entity-relationship model. MySQL Work bench is useful for visualization.</li>\r\n	<li>A many to many relationship (between and addresses) can be done by utilizing a join table.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Databases in Rails</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>When the scaffold generator is run, Rails creates a database migration file. Rails uses SQLite.</li>\r\n	<li>To use another environment, use \"rails server -e production\" to use the production environment.</li>\r\n	<li>SQLite is not a production grade environment.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!--more-->\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The database that rails will use in different environments is specified in db/database.yml</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>The Active Record Design Pattern</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The Active Record Design pattern was named by Martin Fowler. It saves data persistently.</li>\r\n	<li>Classes and objects associated with an Object Oriented language are not compatible w