many, etc.) takes care of this. This is manipulated in the /models folder.</li>\r\n	<li>To manage the association in terms of URL, you need to nest the comments resources under posts.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<a href=\"http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/module3-2.png\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-3057\" src=\"http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/module3-2.png\" alt=\"module3-2\" width=\"833\" height=\"628\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Data Validation</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Data validation ensures that your application operates on clean and useful data (ex. formatting phone numbers). The most common web application security weakness is failure to validate client-side input, and can be solved by cleaning your input.</li>\r\n	<li>Checks include:</li>\r\n	<li>Client side - making sure HTML forms are filled out correctly (used to be in JS but HTML5 has more specific input types).</li>\r\n	<li>Server side:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>DB - these are checks after submission of the HTML for, but it is DB dependent.</li>\r\n	<li>Controller - want to keep logic in controller skinny.</li>\r\n	<li>Model level - checking things before it gets saved to the DB.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Callbacks are methods that get called at certain points in an ActiveRecord object\'s lifecycle.</li>\r\n	<li>Validations are a type of ActiveRecord callback that can be used to ensure valid data -- they are defined within models.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<a href=\"http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/module3-3.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-3058\" src=\"http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/module3-3.png\" alt=\"module3-3\" width=\"1347\" height=\"658\" /></a>','Web Application Architectures: Database Interactions','','inherit','open','open','','3055-revision-v1','','','2015-03-24 16:51:07','2015-03-24 16:51:07','',3055,'http://shipordeliver.com/3055-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3063,1,'2015-03-24 16:51:46','2015-03-24 16:51:46','<p>Here are my notes from the second module of the Web Application Architectures MOOC. I find that the Professor does a great job of explaining a lot of the history and theory behind Ruby and software development, and breaks down them into simple terms.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Ruby on Rails is a software framework for building web apps, copyrighted under MIT Open Source.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Rails is a Ruby gem (prepackaged Ruby app or library). It includes code generators, and additional tools such as RAKE, Webrick, etc.</li>\r\n	<li>The framework is built around the Model-View-Controller pattern.</li><!--more-->\r\n	<li>Criticisms include a lack of scalability (there was a high-profile failure at Twitter) and that it\'s \"magic\" and too automatic. Professor thinks it\'s a part of the natural progression of programming: from Bits to Assembly to HLL to OOP to frameworks.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>To create a new app, type \"$ rails new my_app\" in command line and then \"$ rails server\" to start the web server, and view it at http://localhost:3000.</li>\r\n	<li>Always run \"bundle install\" as the gems necessary are included in the application.</li>\r\n	<li>Architecture:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>/app - Models, Views and Controllers code</li>\r\n	<li>/bin - Helper scripts (bundle, rails, rake)</li>\r\n	<li>/config - App, database & route configuration</li>\r\n	<li>/db - Database schema and migrations</li>\r\n	<li>/Gemfile - Specify the required gems</li>\r\n	<li>/log - Application logging directory</li>\r\n	<li>/public - Webroot of the application</li>\r\n	<li>/tests - Tests - Agile development</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Let\'s build a blog, with 2 users: administrator and author. We will use scaffolding and generators to create some of the components.</li>\r\n	<li>\"$ rake routes\" gives you a list of URLs affiliated with the app.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Rails Philosophy</strong> - Convention over Configuration, Don\'t Repeat Yourself (DRY), and Agile Development (iterative/incremental process).</li>\r\n	<li>DRY - Every piece of information should have a single, unambiguous, authoritative representation within a system.</li>\r\n	<li>Test-driven development (TDD) - build/develop tests first. Behavior-driven development (BDD) is a 2nd-gen agile approach and writes test cases in a natural language that anyone can read.</li>\r\n</ul>','Web Application Architectures: Ruby on Rails','','inherit','open','open','','3049-revision-v1','','','2015-03-24 16:51:46','2015-03-24 16:51:46','',3049,'http://shipordeliver.com/3049-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3064,1,'2015-03-24 18:15:01','2015-03-24 18:15:01','This is the curriculum that I set for myself early on, and constantly iterating on, in my goal to learn software engineering. I believe it\'s a skill that everyone should learn, not just because computers and technology is paving the future for society, but also because it forces one to think in a logical manner. Watch the below video to see my source of inspiration for learning how to code:\r\n\r\n<iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/pvAsqPbz9Ro\" width=\"100%\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe>\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<h2>Future Plans</h2>\r\n<b>Tealeaf Academy:</b>\r\n\r\nBuild Robust and Production Quality Applications\r\n\r\nRapid Prototyping with Ruby on Rails\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>May 2015 - July 2015</h2>\r\n<b>BerkeleyX: </b>\r\n\r\nEngineering Software as a Service Part 1\r\n\r\nEngineering Software as a Service Part 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>March 2015 - April 2015</h2>\r\n<b>The University of New Mexico via Courseera</b>\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Web Application Architectures\" href=\"https://class.coursera.org/webapplications-003\" target=\"_blank\">Web Application Architectures by Greg Heileman</a>\r\n\r\nMy Notes:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Web Application Architectures Introduction and Background\" href=\"http://shipordeliver.com/web-application-architectures-introduction-and-background/\" target=\"_blank\">Web Application Architectures Introduction and Background</a>\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Web Application Architectures: Ruby on Rails\" href=\"http://shipordeliver.com/web-application-architectures-ruby-on-rails/\" target=\"_blank\">Web Application Architectures: Ruby on Rails </a>\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Web Application Architectures: Database Interactions\" href=\"http://shipordeliver.com/web-application-architectures-database-interactions/\" target=\"_blank\">Web Application Architectures: Database Interactions</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>November 2014 - February 2015</h2>\r\n<a title=\"Making a Social Network From Scratch\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLA7F9875BD031DC16\" target=\"_blank\">Build Your Own Social Network Series by HowCode</a> + Bootstrap Hacking\r\n\r\nSeries Here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLA7F9875BD031DC16 (playlist)\r\n\r\nA 43-part video series culminating in my portfolio piece: <a title=\"Jaded\" href=\"http://shipordeliver.com/projects/socialnetwork/\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Jaded, a social network for product/project professionals</strong></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>2012 - 2014</h2>\r\n<strong>Simple Task LLC</strong> - I was employed as a front-end developer and junior Project Manager at a devshop for about a little over a year. I went in knowing raw HTML and CSS, and was thrown into the world of software development by building interfaces for eCommerce sites and business systems.\r\n\r\nI learned HTML, CSS, Javascript, PHP, and Python during my time here.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>CodeAcademy</b>\r\n\r\n100% Python track\r\n\r\n100% Javascript track','My Curriculum','','inherit','open','open','','3001-revision-v1','','','2015-03-24 18:15:01','2015-03-24 18:15:01','',3001,'http://shipordeliver.com/3001-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3066,1,'2015-03-30 20:21:43','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<ol>\n	<li>Re(write) a test</li>\n	<li>Check if test fails (it will fail)</li>\n	<li>Write production code</li>\n	<li>Run all tests</li>\n</ol>\nhttp://testfirst.org\n\nMore agile, more main tenable','Why Test Driven Development','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-03-30 20:21:43','2015-03-30 20:21:43','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?p=3066',0,'post','',0),(3067,1,'2015-03-30 20:20:25','2015-03-30 20:20:25','<ol>\r\n	<li>Re(write) a test</li>\r\n	<li>Check if test fails (it will fail)</li>\r\n	<li>Write production code</li>\r\n	<li>Run all tests</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nMore agile, more main tenable','Why Test Driven Development','','inherit','open','open','','3066-revision-v1','','','2015-03-30 20:20:25','2015-03-30 20:20:25','',3066,'http://shipordeliver.com/3066-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3068,1,'2015-04-02 12:17:13','2015-04-02 12:17:13','I\'ve been getting a lot of questions about how I ended up with a front-end development role immediately out of college with no Computer Science background. Keep in mind that I never said I was amazing in that role (hence why I applied to <a title=\"Fullstack Academy\" href=\"http://fullstackacademy.com\" target=\"_blank\">Fullstack Academy</a>), but for those trying to break into the industry-- here\'s some advice.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>The Early Years</h3>\r\nGrowing up, I was always obsessed with computers but quite fearful of the technology and digital industries. My father was among the new wave of Chinese immigrants to the United States who sought growth potential in the early 90’s. After a few years of saving up from a waiting job, he made the commute every weekend from Queens to Connecticut to get his Master’s in Computer Science at the University of Bridgeport.\r\n\r\nGiven that my mother worked on the weekends and I had no substitute caretaker, my dad would frequently take nine-year-old me with him to campus, and have me sit in on the classes. I recall a sense of youthful pride as I sat in those classrooms with people three-to-four times my age, jotting down notes on random subjects I could not comprehend, but pretended I did-- with words like “systems”, “kernel”, and “Java” making up the majority of my scribbles.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nFor a number of years after my dad graduated, I knew I wanted to be a computer scientist. My father found work at a startup called GiantBear programming in Java, and for the first time in our lives, we had financial stability and bright prospects.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>Then the Bubble Burst</h3>\r\nThe dot-com bubble quickly put an end to that-- at the turn of the century, GiantBear was acquired by a company in Seattle, and my dad was let go.\r\n\r\nWe struggled financially for the next few years-- with my dad returning to work as a waiter and our family having to live in a small basement apartment. The worst hit, however, was to my passion for computers-- I naively associated the software industry early on with fleeting dreams and a lack of stability, and quickly found interests elsewhere.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>College Years</h3>\r\nAbout a decade later, I chose to major in Economics and Political Science in college, and pursued business opportunities on the side to bolster my resume. Around sophomore year, I caught the entrepreneurship bug, and decided to try my hand at a side business. At the time, I had been studying for the LSAT with plans of attending law school, and discovered that there was an enormous amount of resources online for test-takers. Having dabbled in digital marketing in high school, I quickly built a site using PHP, Javascript, HTML, and CSS called The Standardized Genius.\r\n\r\nThe blog/review site acted as a one-stop-shop resource for standardized test takers and inform visitors of the best resources for their specific exams. I also interviewed test-prep company owners and teachers, and included commentary/discussion on the site to try and build a community. After about six months of self-taught coding and business hustle, I made my first dollar when someone bought a used LSAT textbook via an Amazon referral link on the page.\r\n\r\nThe Standardized Genius grew for about a year more, but some legal issues with one of the test tutors I interviewed forced me to shut it down. However, that venture was enough to spark my passion for computer science again-- I found myself more drawn to adding features and maintaining the server than I was in getting more clicks or content up.\r\n\r\nI found it all fascinating-- learning how functions and arrays worked in jQuery effects, manipulating SQL databases, creating secure connections-- all this knowledge kept me hungry for a deeper understanding of the internet and software.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h4>I\'m Not Exactly Sure What I\'m Doing</h4>\r\nJust prior to graduation, I leveraged my network and internships at startups to secure a coding gig with a web-dev shop. This proved to be fortuitous, as I had the pleasure of meeting my future mentor, a world-class programmer, who taught me the ropes.\r\n\r\nHaving just come in as a self-taught front-end developer, he and my colleagues made me want to be a real software engineer; we went beyond the markup languages and dove deep into SSH, eMacs, ETL methods, data structures, and SE methodologies in delivering world-class business solutions for our clients. I’ve never been as excited to start my days as I had in my year there.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, our small team quickly made some business errors, and the dev shop could no longer afford to keep me on. After realizing a restructuring was inevitable, I moved on to a less technical role as a Project Manager. Though project management enables me to have some exposure to development, I yearn for the days when I knew I was going to learn and grow. Software engineering’s learning curve is among the steepest of any vocation, and I can’t think of a deeper professional satisfaction than in immersing myself in this technical world.','How I Became a Developer Without a Technical Degree','','publish','open','open','','what-inspired-you-to-code','','','2015-04-03 19:57:52','2015-04-03 19:57:52','',0,'http://shipordeliver.co