ortunately, our small team quickly made some business errors, and the dev shop could no longer afford to keep me on. After realizing a restructuring was inevitable, I moved on to a less technical role as a Project Manager. Though project management enables me to have some exposure to development, I yearn for the days when I knew I was going to learn and grow. Software engineering’s learning curve is among the steepest of any vocation, and I can’t think of a deeper professional satisfaction than in immersing myself in this technical world. I also believe that the understanding one attains in this field opens doors into many other opportunities-- whether it be genome analysis at a hospital or providing cyber security at a bank-- that will allow me to maximize my potential to society.','What Inspired You to Code?','','inherit','open','open','','3068-revision-v1','','','2015-04-02 12:17:13','2015-04-02 12:17:13','',3068,'http://shipordeliver.com/3068-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3070,1,'2015-04-03 02:22:44','2015-04-03 02:22:44','[parallax photourl=\"http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/code.jpeg\" verticaloffset=\"280\" title=\"Software Is The Equalizer\" text=\"Who I am and what is my mission?\" textmargin=\"100\" overlaycolor=\"#222\" overlayopacity=\"0.75\"][/parallax]\r\n\r\n[widerow customclass=\"white\"]\r\n\r\n[row_fluid]\r\n\r\n[span4]\r\n[dropcap custom_class=\"big\"]Autodidactism is the future. Why is formal education, and specifically formal computer science and engineering education, so expensive? Private \"elite\" universities charge hundreds of thousands of dollars per student for a few hours of lectures that are largely slept through. For-profit schools follow the same model, but usually provide no semblance of an education or post-graduate opportunities. Bootcamps seem to be paving a new route, but their accessibility to those without the financial resources is a concern.[/dropcap]\r\n[/span4]\r\n[span4]\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">As a semi-technical professional working within the internet/technology industry, I quickly realized that to truly be effective in this field, I needed to learn programming. Not just hack some code-- I mean truly understand the underlying theory, components, and frameworks of computer science. As I explored formal educational options, I was shocked and outraged at the prices. Education used to be an investment. You were granted access to knowledge and a network for a monetary cost. It was usually a good investment-- you would gain skills you could apply.</p>\r\n[/span4]\r\n[span4]\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">With a looming student loan bubble and an unlimited amount of free, quality resources, it doesn\'t seem to make sense to fork over hard-earned money for what I can find online and in books. This blog is my attempt to uncover the hundreds of free and low-cost alternatives, and to prove that autodidactism can foster skills and talent equal to thousands of dollars and years spent in universities. The joy of learning should not be limited to those with resources, and I am here to prove that.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">- Jacob J. Zhang</p>\r\n[/span4]\r\n[/row_fluid][/widerow]\r\n\r\n[widerow customclass=\"\"][row_fluid]\r\n\r\n[heading_entrance title=\"How I\'m Learning\" text=\"These are the free or low-cost alternatives to formal education that I am using right now to learn software engineering.\"]\r\n\r\n[/row_fluid]\r\n\r\n[row_fluid]\r\n\r\n[span4]\r\n\r\n[skills value=\"50\" size=\"200\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" fgcolor=\"#222222\" donutwidth=\"8\" title=\"MOOCs\" fontsize=\"32px\"]\r\n\r\n[/span4]\r\n\r\n[span4]\r\n\r\n[skills value=\"25\" size=\"200\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" fgcolor=\"#222222\" donutwidth=\"8\" title=\"Books\" fontsize=\"32px\"]\r\n\r\n[/span4]\r\n\r\n[span4]\r\n\r\n[skills value=\"25\" size=\"200\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" fgcolor=\"#222222\" donutwidth=\"8\" title=\"On the Job\" fontsize=\"32px\"]\r\n\r\n[/span4]\r\n\r\n[/ro