s/2014/05/marketing.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3091,1,'2015-04-04 13:38:15','2015-04-04 13:38:15','[dropcap custom_class=\"normal\"]Please note that what I\'m about to say only applies to startups. People who have a Master\'s degree in Business Administration from an elite school are generally folks who\'ve gone to amazing undergraduate institutions, worked at some top-notch companies and performed well, and scored high enough on the grueling GMAT to land themselves in a six-figure job. In no way am I discrediting MBA-holders-- as a matter of fact, I may get an MBA some day.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Corporate Life</strong>\r\n\r\nIt\'s a stamp of not just intelligence, but presumably a deep and thorough understanding of accounting, finance, and marketing; a measure of your social and professional network; and often a strong brand on your resume that gets your foot in the door at a some great firms. [/dropcap]\r\n\r\nBut note that distinction: a <strong>large</strong> company, like a Google or Con Edison, has employee counts in the thousands. MBAs fit cleanly in such an organization; with the company already massively profitable, they can take their time learning the ins-and-outs of the technology or business that they represent. They can focus on getting really good, to the level of mastery, at one thing, and ride that one skill until they peak career-wise. There is absolutely no way that\'s happening at a startup.<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<strong>The Startup Grind</strong>\r\n\r\nI\'ve worked or consulted at several startups in the past, in technical and non-technical capacities, both locally and remote. Of the ones who have saw profitably and success, there was a common theme: a lack of MBAs and a handful of self-taught (this is important) full-stack marketers.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Full-stack of Marketing</strong>\r\n\r\nThe full-stack marketers were the hustlers. They had typically mastered at least one important skill (sales, design, marketing), but could also do the many, many other things (building landing pages, making cold calls, managing email campaigns) that needed to get done. They were unafraid that any function was outside their job description, and instead embraced the chaotic nature of startups, using it as fuel to focus on one thing: <strong>growth</strong>.\r\n\r\nThe idea originated with full-stack development. Engineering roles at startups began to require more breadth than depth, and for good reason. Marcelo Calbucci describes this beautifully <a title=\"GeekWire\" href=\"http://www.geekwire.com/2013/commentary-startup-marketing-minds-aka-fullstack-marketers/\" target=\"_blank\">in GeekWire</a>:\r\n\r\n[blockquote]We all knew what it meant to be a “jack of all trades” developer at a startup, but the term gave clarity to why “full-stack developers” were critical to build an early startup team. You can’t afford to have a VP of Engineering whose whole job is to manage the engineering team because you don’t have an engineering team. You can’t afford to have a DBA just to manage the database, because your database doesn’t have enough data. At the same time, every week you need a few hours of DBA, a few hours of “VP-ing,” a few hours of architecture design, a few hours of HTML/CSS coding, a few hours of API integration, etc. The solution startups found is to have full-stack developers.[/blockquote]\r\n\r\nIn the same way, you can\'t have a non-technical person who solely books meetings. Or a person whose sole job is to create email campaigns. With a firm under 10-20 people, when you\'re just getting off the ground, there\'s a definite need for hustlers who can hit all major pain points in the organization, and create value as soon as possible.\r\n\r\nThat also explains why startups are some of the best training grounds on the planet-- you\'re forced into a role where you must learn to keep up and contribute. You are forced to grow as a professional, and often have to teach yourself things as they come up. Google search is your friend, and luckily, the software industry is also especially keen on sharing and spreading wisdom.\r\n\r\n<strong>Back to MBAs</strong>\r\n\r\nUltimately what their counterpart MBAs bring to the table is a skill-set that is useful once the business is actually established. At some point, you\'ll need to figure out the logistics of corporate governance, dividend distribution, etc.-- things a formal business degree teaches well. I assure you that when you\'re having problems getting your product completed in time or getting your first customer, your concerns won\'t involve financial instruments, or how much of the annual budget to set aside for R&amp;D. You need a hustler who gets users.\r\n\r\nSo-- at least in the world of startups-- step aside MBAs, make way for the full stack marketer.','Step Aside MBAs, Make Way for the Full Stack Marketer','','inherit','open','open','','2858-revision-v1','','','2015-04-04 13:38:15','2015-04-04 13:38:15','',2858,'http://shipordeliver.com/2858-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3092,1,'2015-04-04 13:39:12','2015-04-04 13:39:12','[dropcap custom_class=\"normal\"]Please note that what I\'m about to say only applies to startups. People who have a Master\'s degree in Business Administration from an elite school are generally folks who\'ve gone to amazing undergraduate institutions, worked at some top-notch companies and performed well, and scored high enough on the grueling GMAT to land themselves in a six-figure job. In no way am I discrediting MBA-holders-- as a matter of fact, I may get an MBA some day.\r\n\r\n<h4>The Corporate Life</h4>\r\n\r\nIt\'s a stamp of not just intelligence, but presumably a deep and thorough understanding of accounting, finance, and marketing; a measure of your social and professional network; and often a strong brand on your resume that gets your foot in the door at a some great firms. [/dropcap]\r\n\r\nBut note that distinction: a <strong>large</strong> company, like a Google or Con Edison, has