pen','','3111-revision-v1','','','2015-04-06 12:48:25','2015-04-06 12:48:25','',3111,'http://shipordeliver.com/3111-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3117,1,'2015-04-09 03:59:35','2015-04-09 03:59:35','I\'ve been on a bit of a learning spree lately-- a man on a mission to absorb all potentially useful knowledge. My mind\'s been acting like a sponge, hopefully retaining everything I\'ve been reading, watching, and studying. It\'s a shame that this phenomenon isn\'t a more permanent thing; it seems to come in waves. After a trigger of sorts, I\'ll find myself experiencing bliss upon metaphorically digging a hole in several books, but this quickly comes to a peak and dissolves into complacency and boredom quickly.\r\n\r\nWhat I\'ve noticed, however, is that despite the duration, I retain a considerable amount more. I am actively engaged in the learning process without realizing it, and it\'s primarily because I\'m having a good time. As a project manager, I\'ve tried to pick up and read through hoards of books on project management, but I cannot finish them as I would a mystery novel. They\'re written in such a dry, factual manner-- reminiscent of college textbooks-- but that\'s not the reason they bore me.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nThe first reason is because as a practicing project manager, I understand there\'s such a disconnect between the advice dispensed by gurus and actual application. Real project management is less about constraints, dependencies, and charts than it is clear written and verbal communication and people skills. The second reason, and the primary reason I write this post, is that because of reason one, I don\'t have a intrinsic purpose for reading it. As a practicing project manager, I am gaining hands-on experience that counts. I could pretend like it matters how I format my project plans, or the methods of prioritization of tasks, but having worked in the role for so long, I know what truly matters.\r\n\r\nTo extend my point, I know for sure I would thus be much more engaged, and happy, to take a public speaking course or read a book on emotional intelligence. Those things matter to me, on a deep, intrinsic level. Our brains are smart enough to filter through what matters and what doesn\'t, and try to trick it as we may (who actually does every single reading assignment in college?), our engagement and interest levels will always shine through in our level of joy while learning.\r\n\r\nSo here comes the problem with traditional academia, and this comes as no insult to any specific school but as a criticism of all forms of schooling worldwide: it\'s an open fact that a large portion of students are bored out of their minds a good amount of the time they are in school. Based on my observation above, this becomes problematic, being that they are essentially wasting their time on knowledge and courses they don\'t care about and will probably never use. This is why many students do much better in college, or graduate school, when they get to choose an area of interest instead of being forced to sit through a \"comprehensive\" curriculum.\r\n\r\nLiberal arts proponents will argue that a wide-ranging curriculum exposes students to new ideas and interests. I agree with the intention-- as Steve Jobs once said, and I paraphrase, innovation comes from people having different experiences in life and contributing their uniqueness. However, those experiences should come in the form of dull books. They should be lived and breathed.\r\n\r\nI don\'t have a fix for the system in place, but it is certainly telling that vocational schools, online courses, and development bootcamps are gaining tons of traction. An investment in one of those will likely go considerably farther than a traditional $160k liberal arts degree.','The Joy of Constant Learning and My Beef with Academia','','inherit','open','open','','2936-revision-v1','','','2015-04-09 03:59:35','2015-04-09 03:59:35','',2936,'http://shipordeliver.com/2936-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3125,1,'2015-11-27 17:39:08','2015-11-27 17:39:08','<strong>The Problem</strong>\r\n\r\nI\'ve gained a few pounds recently as a result of stress (never work full time and take more than 2 graduate courses at once if you want to retain your sanity), and have been trying many different methods to lose the weight. Among these are <a href=\"http://iifym.com/\" target=\"_blank\">IIFYM</a>, <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/The-Fast-5-Diet-Lifestyle/dp/0977253406\" target=\"_blank\">Fast-5</a>, and basic calorie counting.\r\n\r\nNone of these have worked thus far-- but I don\'t blame the programs for my failure. They each have many testimonials from successful practitioners who, I\'m sure, are more than happy to give a little ab-flex in tribute of their results. The problem, as always with habit change, lies in my brain and processes: I\'m simply too hardwired to eat delicious food, and fail to create a system that allows me to stick to these methods.\r\n\r\nThe typical process is that I\'ll find a program online or via a friend, and become enamored with the promises of lean, washboard abs. I\'ll study the rules and dissect why the program works, and quickly set about starting the diet. I\'ll eat pretty well on day one, fasting until 5pm or counting my calories or whatnot. Same with day two. Then, day three arrives, and I kind of \"forget\". By the time I realize I\'ve wrecked day three, it\'s too late to salvage the day, so I\'ll rationalize a feeding frenzy for the next few days as I try to get back on the bandwagon.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Hmm... Sounds Familiar.</b>\r\n\r\nI\'ve been thinking a lot about how similar this is to a software project. Everyone\'s always excited and thrilled at the very beginning, but find themselves quickly dealing with unexpected hurdles and challenges. In the same way a PM cannot predict a feature being more difficult to implement than expected, a dieter cannot forecast an invitation to a friend\'s birthday at that awesome Japanese buffet in Flushing.\r\n\r\n<em>If dieting is so similar to a software project, why not treat like one, and apply good Project Management practices to the project?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>The Solution</strong>\r\n\r\nI thought about how I would approach it, and have laid out some ideas that would troubleshoot a lot of the causes for my failed dieting in the past:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Have a start date and end date.People will always have a goal in mind. Mine was \"six pack abs\". But how do we quantify it? If we are able to boil down the process of fat loss into simple math (using time estimates), we can guesstimate a deadline and work towards it.\r\n\r\nAt this writing, I am 180 pounds at 5\'9. According to multiple calculators online, with my bodyfat %, I\'ll need to drop about 20 pounds to see a six pack. At the recommendation a pound a week, I can achieve this in 20 weeks, or by mid-April.</li>\r\n	<li>Have a plan broken up into phases, and then tasks.Once we have \"lose 20 pounds of fat by April\" as a goal, we can break it up into sub-goals. For the sake of this \"project\", we can call them milestones. Here are some random milestones based on my example:\r\n\r\n<b>5 pounds lost</b> - end of 2015<b>\r\n</b><strong>10 pounds lost</strong> - end of January \'16\r\n\r\nFor our tasks, we could break it up into nutrition and workouts. The tasks could be, every day, perform these two activities: 1) eat at or around 1800-2000 calories, 2) complete a 45-60 minute strength training workout or run</li>\r\n	<li>Assess the risks and manage them.A good Project Manager needs to be able do risk assessment and then develop strategies to manage it. Some inherent risks are (and their solutions are):\r\n\r\n1. Going over 2000 calories for too many days in a row - there are many ways to combat this. For me, I\'ve noticed that eating later in the day helps with appetite, so that\'s a possible solution. Another is reducing appetite by drinking green tea and coffee. A third idea is to eat food that is high in fiber and good fats so that I\'m full often. It\'s critical to integrate some of these ideas in.\r\n\r\n2. Missing a workout too many days in a row - same with point#1, causes could be laziness, fatigue, or a lack of time. Some solutions include reducing workouts per week to a minimum of 3, learning to perform calisthenics at home, or getting a workout buddy to keep me motivated.</li>\r\n	<li>Have an eye on change management.Another issue I\'ve run into is that my goals will change. Building huge muscles and getting extremely lean sound like they\'re the same goal, but one requires lifting low reps and heavy (and eating a lot), and the other is mostly about dieting while maintaining your current muscle base. The solution here is simple: keep your eye on the ball, I can always build muscle later but let\'s focus on getting the body fat percentage low first.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Check-ins and Status Reports</strong>\r\n\r\nWith the plan in mind, we\'ll need to consider how to determine if we are on the path to completing the project.\r\n\r\nOne way is to simply have a check-in weekly, where you record your weight and ensure that it is going down more often that it\'s going up. Due to weight fluctuations, a daily check-in would be too much, and too distracting. Additionally, it probably makes sense to record your calories on given day, so you can ensure that you are sticking to the process.\r\n\r\nA monthly photo would also be beneficial to be able to see changes from month to month.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Without Further Ado</strong>\r\n\r\nI will be embarking on this attempt starting next Monday, November 30th. Please follow <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/147jJUa8UgbMaDE4CqldIYuXcMG7lRMntbcg98OIy-WI/\">my progress here</a>.','The Project Method to Getting Shredded: An Experiment','','publish','open','open','','project-method-to-shred','','','2015-11-27 17:45:35','2015-11-27 17:45:35','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?p=3125',0,'post','',0),(3126,1,'2015-07-30 17:17:01','2015-07-30 17:17:01','','The Project Manager\'s Approach to Weight Loss','','inherit','open','open','','3125-revision-v1','','','2015-07-30 17:17:01','2015-07-30 17:17:01','',3125,'http://shipordeliver.com/3125-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3135,1,'2015-08-04 03:37:29','2015-08-04 03:37:29','At software companies, the software engineers write code and handle technical matters-- that\'s a given. However, many non-engineers at technology (or technology-based) companies seem to use that as an excuse to steer clear of anything to do with code or complexity.\r\n\r\nAside from the typical complaints of older coworkers not knowing how to adjust browser size correctly, or losing grasp of where their chat window is, I have seen instances where even PMs have been unable to do their job properly because they did not have a solid enough technical understanding of the product. Project and product managers cannot make good trade-offs on features or timeline without being in-tune with what\'s going on in engineering. Similarly, client managers simply cannot give adequate status reports or obtain requests from clients on things they don\'t grasp.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/nontechnical.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-3166\" src=\"http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/nontechnical.jpg\" alt=\"nontechnical\" width=\"335\" height=\"335\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMany other positions, including varying roles in marketing, finance, and even upper management are often afflicted by this fear of the technical. This is a terrible problem, especially at software or digital companies, where an understanding of technical matters is important in:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Working collaboratively between departments</li>\r\n	<li>Client communication</li>\r\n	<li>Requirements writing</li>\r\n	<li>Understanding timelines and delays</li>\r\n	<li>Selecting the proper marketing channels</li>\r\n	<li>Getting things done</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThus, at least of the fundamental understanding of the following will go a long way in improving workplace collaboration and productivity at a tech company:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>1) Understand (at a high level) how your product is built.</strong>\r\n\r\nObviously, there is no need to know what the entire software stack is, or even what framework is used. However, something simple, such as \"Wordpress\'s UI is written in HTML, CSS, and Javascript and there is a PHP backend that writes to a MySQL database\" would be sufficient for most tasks.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>2) Get comfortable with the terminology.</strong>\r\n\r\nKnow what the different programming languages are, and where they\'re used. As a general rule of thumb, the big web languages are Javascript, Ruby, Python, and PHP. Android development is done in Java, and iPhone apps are written in either Objective-C or Swift.\r\n\r\nKnow that a database is where most of the actual \"data\" is stored, and that most applications simply take inputs and write them to a database. Then, when you place a call for that information, it is retrieved from the database as well.\r\n\r\nWhen a developer tells you that they need to clear the cache, check the error log, perform QA, or document an API, please know what they\'re talking about. And if not, feel free to ask.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/carlcheoprogramming.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-3168\" src=\"http://shipordeliver.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/carlcheoprogramming.png\" alt=\"Programming\" width=\"2000\" height=\"2210\" /></a>(Copyright Carlcheo.com)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>3) Learn the difference between front-end and back-end.</strong>\r\n\r\nNot all development is the same. There is the user interface that most end users interact with-- for web products, this is controlled by HTML and CSS. The back-end is where and how the information is processed, and is called \"back\"-end because it is stealthily hidden from users.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>4) Get to know the SDLC.</strong>\r\n\r\nThe Software Development Life Cycle varies from methodology to methodology, and company to company, but in general, it boils down to the following:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Define - what are we building?</li>\r\n	<li>Discovery - how will we build it?</li>\r\n	<li>Design - here\'s a visual of how we\'ll build it.</li>\r\n	<li>Develop - building it...</li>\r\n	<li>Deliver - make sure what we built works.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>5) Recognize the complexities of software.</strong>\r\n\r\nSoftware development, whether it be machine-level or web, is incredibly challenging. The engineering aspect of it requires developers to always be producing something new out of what exists. Most industries have their workers take what works and repeat it. Software engineering forces you to create completely new things.\r\n\r\nAs a result, you can very rarely tell how long things will take. When an engineer gives an estimated level of effort, don\'t question them unless you were an engineer yourself who\'s worked on a similar feature or bug. Software is complex, let the engineers solve these challenging problems without burdening them with harsh deadlines or micro-management. If something really needs to get done fast, a conversation with the developer on trade-offs and compromises goes a lot further than putting more pressure on your colleagues.','Things All Non-Engineers Should Know at a Tech Company','','publish','open','open','','things-all-non-engineers-should-know-at-a-tech-company','','','2015-08-04 03:39:12','2015-08-04 03:39:12','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?p=3135',0,'post','',0),(3136,1,'2015-08-02 15:50:59','2015-08-02 15:50:59','Software engineers write code and handle technical matters-- that\'s a given. However, many n