lves after previous successes. I think it was actually Tucker Max who once wrote that success is easy, you just need to find someone who\'s done what you\'ve done and replicate the steps.\r\n\r\nThis is kind of true, but only for mediocrity. What you\'re doing is following in someone\'s footsteps, which works, but it\'s easy to forget that there\'s so a huge amount of variables that are out of your control. The year you live in, for example.\r\n\r\nBefore reading up on Cal Newport\'s Career Craftsman theory, I was incredibly career ADD. I, and many others of my generation, have probably changed our minds on what we wanted to do dozens-- if not hundreds-- of times. And the worst part was that I\'d get incredibly attached to an ideal. It was a mixture of so many pieces of career advice gone wrong: aim for the stars, but be realistic, go for your passion, but everything has its ups and downs, etc.\r\n\r\nThen I\'d find a role model who did what I wanted to do and I\'d check their biography or Linkedin (we are technologists, after all) and try to see how I could emulate their paths to greatness. A few problems arise when this occurs.','The Importance of Doing Something Different','','draft','open','open','','importance-of-doing-something-different','','','2015-09-09 16:54:22','2015-09-09 16:54:22','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?p=3175',0,'post','',0),(3176,1,'2015-08-04 11:23:55','2015-08-04 11:23:55','','25 Quick Ways to Repair Your Creativity Muscle','','inherit','open','open','','3175-revision-v1','','','2015-08-04 11:23:55','2015-08-04 11:23:55','',3175,'http://shipordeliver.com/3175-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3179,1,'2015-08-04 11:26:56','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','The Definitive Guide to Startup Tools in 2015','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-08-04 11:26:56','2015-08-04 11:26:56','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?p=3179',0,'post','',0),(3180,1,'2015-08-04 11:26:56','2015-08-04 11:26:56','','The Definitive Guide to Startup Tools in 2015','','inherit',