n this occurs.','The Importance of Doing Something Different','','inherit','open','open','','3175-revision-v1','','','2015-09-09 16:54:22','2015-09-09 16:54:22','',3175,'http://shipordeliver.com/3175-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3193,1,'2015-09-09 17:36:34','2015-09-09 17:36:34','I\'ve always been fascinated about the study of success. Though many will argue that America is not as meritocratic as most think, it\'s still much more possible to go from rags to riches here than anywhere else in the world. The land of opportunity is beautiful in that sense, that though there\'s still work to do, it doesn\'t matter where you grow up or who your parents are-- there is <em>some</em> route to success.\r\n\r\nOf course, success could mean many different things as well. Financial wealth, the most popular metric, is certainly something that comes to mind\r\n\r\nI used to memorize celebrity heights and weights, career paths, ... love biographies It also helps that I\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLong attention span\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nClean Dopamine Receptors\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNatural social intelligence\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','What Do Successful People Actually Have in Common?','','inherit','open','open','','3185-revision-v1','','','2015-09-09 17:36:34','2015-09-09 17:36:34','',3185,'http://shipordeliver.com/3185-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3194,1,'2015-09-09 17:37:15','2015-09-09 17:37:15','I\'ve always been fascinated about the study of success. Though many will argue that America is not as meritocratic as most think, it\'s still much more possible to go from rags to riches here than anywhere else in the world. The land of opportunity is beautiful in that sense, that though there\'s still work to do, it doesn\'t matter where you grow up or who your parents are-- there is <em>some</em> route to success.\r\n\r\nOf course, success could mean many different things as well. Financial wealth, the most popular metric, is certainly something that comes to mind\r\n\r\nI used to memorize celebrity heights and weights, career paths, ... love biographies It also helps that I\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLong attention span\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nClean Dopamine Receptors\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNatural social intelligence\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHuge readers','What Do Successful People Actually Have in Common?','','inherit','open','open','','3185-revision-v1','','','2015-09-09 17:37:15','2015-09-09 17:37:15','',3185,'http://shipordeliver.com/3185-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3196,1,'2015-09-11 15:56:29','0000-00-00 00:00:00','If you are the average ambitious millennial, you are probably discontent. I don\'t want to say depressed, because I think as a whole, our generation is pretty happy-- but there is an itch we can\'t scratch. There\'s a place in our souls where we are simply unsatisfied. You could call it a <em>longing for more,</em> a need to do and be better, or simply a desire to change.\r\n\r\nIt\'s like that scene in How to Make it In America, where Ben meets his drunk, ex-girlfriend Rachel on his apartment steps late one night. They talk about their relationship and why it failed, and one phrase always lingers in my head. It\'s when Ben, frustrated that she isn\'t giving him clear answers, asks, \"what exactly do you want?\" Rachel\'s answer? \"I just want more.\"\r\n\r\nThroughout life, we\'ve been taught that quality matters greater than quantity, and that we ultimately should not keep pursuing extraneous desires. Buddhism, a beloved spiritual practice by many a millennial, says that excess will not make us happy. And yet, that is not what we learn, for humans growing up learn more from observing behavior than anything else.\r\n\r\nIt is tremendously hard to accept that one should be happy with what one has, when her mother and father are fighting over money. Or when all her friends take on massive debt in an effort to make more money. ....\r\n\r\ncurrent state of affairs\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIt comes from other sources too. The \"Facebook Effect\" is real and validated by science-- Facebook as a platform is a listing of your friends\' and family members\' accomplishments, vacations, and relationships. Once in a while, you will encounter a sad thought or a heart-wrenching story, but for the most part, people will post what they want people to know. What you don\'t see are their daily bad habits, their hardships, their annoyances-- stuff you encounter daily but think no one else does.\r\n\r\nThen you have entertainment. I\'m looking at you, E! and TMZ. The glamorizing of celebrities, who can afford to always look perfect, is detrimental to societal perception.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nfallacy is that once you get there- 20 year old ceos suffer\r\n\r\nwhat to do about it-- live in the present, appreciate what you have, be content','The Problem With Ambitious Millennials','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-09-11 15:56:29','2015-09-11 15:56:29','',0,'http://shipordeliver.com/?page_id=3196',0,'page','',0),(3197,1,'2015-09-11 15:56:29','2015-09-11 15:56:29','If you are the average ambitious millennial, you are probably discontent. I don\'t want to say depressed, because I think as a whole, our generation is pretty happy-- but there is an itch we can\'t scratch. There\'s a place in our souls where we are simply unsatisfied. You could call it a <em>longing for more,</em> a need to do and be better, or simply a desire to change.\r\n\r\nIt\'s like that scene in How to Make it In America, where Ben meets his drunk, ex-girlfriend Rachel on his apartment steps late one night. They talk about their relationship and why it failed, and one phrase always lingers in my head. It\'s when Ben, frustrated that she isn\'t giving him clear answers, asks, \"what exactly do you want?\" Rachel\'s answer? \"I just want more.\"\r\n\r\nThroughout life, we\'ve been taught that quality matters greater than quantity, and that we ultimately should not keep pursuing extraneous desires. Buddhism, a beloved spiritual practice by m