nd think he has some unique ideas. One of them is to become an \"idea machine\", whereby you generate at least 10 ideas a day in the interest of working out your \"idea muscle.\" The point is not to come up with a good idea to capitalize on (though it is great if that happens), the point is to always be able to think for yourself and generate ideas on the whim, since Altucher argues that ideas are a new form of currency.\r\n\r\nHere are 10 random product ideas that I came up with today:\r\n\r\n1. A service that automatically generates a Wordpress profile based on user-selected filters.\r\n\r\n2. A project management toolkit that helps make PM\'s jobs easier. Like a mint.com for Project Managers, it would aggregate JIRA, Trello, Asana, etc.\r\n\r\n3. An application of the Jerry Seinfeld \"X chaining\" habit rule that is automatically triggered. Maybe make it an interactive phone screen that forces you to mark if you accomplished your desired activity or neglected to stay away from a bad activity.\r\n\r\n4. A service that finds you a song based on what your <em>closest</em> friends listen to. Sort of like what Spotify does, but it would only source from friends you interact with regularly.\r\n\r\n5. Summarizer - takes books, make 1-paragraph \"highlight reels\" out of them, and crowdsource them.\r\n\r\n6. Auto Work Out Logger - a mobile app that is worn during exercise that counts the number of reps you do based on movement.\r\n\r\n7. A calculator/recommender where you enter your measurements and a specific pair of jeans is recommended for you by fit.\r\n\r\n8. A codecanyon or marketplace for data visualization code.\r\n\r\n9. Ratemycourses.com - Like a ratemyprofessor.com for college courses themselves, moreso to see if you\'d actually enjoy learning the material versus seeing how good the professor is.\r\n\r\n10. MyCareer - a service that builds a profile off your social media accounts and recommends a career.','Random Product Ideas - 11/24/15','','publish','open','