hat\'s a possible solution. Another is reducing appetite by drinking green tea and coffee. A third idea is to eat food that is high in fiber and good fats so that I\'m full often. It\'s critical to integrate some of these ideas in.\n\n2. Missing a workout too many days in a row - same with point#1, causes could be laziness, fatigue, or a lack of time. Some solutions include reducing workouts per week to a minimum of 3, learning to perform calisthenics at home, or getting a workout buddy to keep me motivated.</li>\n	<li>Have an eye on change management.Another issue I\'ve run into is that my goals will change. Building huge muscles and getting extremely lean sound like they\'re the same goal, but one requires lifting low reps and heavy (and eating a lot), and the other is mostly about dieting while maintaining your current muscle base. The solution here is simple: keep your eye on the ball, I can always build muscle later but let\'s focus on getting the body fat percentage low first.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Check-ins and Status Reports</strong>\n\nWith the plan in mind, we\'ll need to consider how to determine if we are on the path to completing the project.\n\nOne way is to simply have a check-in weekly, where you record your weight and ensure that it is going down more often that it\'s going up. Due to weight fluctuations, a daily check-in would be too much, and too distracting. Additionally, it probably makes sense to record your calories on given day, so you can ensure that you are sticking to the process.\n\nA monthly photo would also be beneficial to be able to see changes from month to month.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Without Further Ado</strong>\n\nI will be embarking on this attempt starting next Monday, November 30th. Please follow my progress here.','The Project Method to Getting Shredded: An Experiment','','inherit','open','open','','3125-autosave-v1','','','2015-11-27 17:42:44','2015-11-27 17:42:44','',3125,'http://shipordeliver.com/3125-autosave-v1/',