with, I plan to work as a software engineer for 2-3 years and familiarize myself well with product and engineering at a tech company. After that, I\'ll start applying to Product roles.\"\r\n\r\nHe is certainly not wrong that he would benefit from the technical training and from work experience with engineers, but the larger question is ignored-- why not just apply directly to product management positions now? There is no greater substitute than real world experience.\r\n\r\nWhen I was preparing for the LSAT for law school applications, I was pretty active on a bunch of LSAT forums and in study groups. People would routinely ask what the best publications to read were to improve their vocabulary, whether sudoku helped with logic games, and sometimes even which law school had the most attractive student body. Interestingly enough, the highest scorers could probably attribute 80-90% of their scores to plowing through practice tests and learning from their mistakes each time.\r\n\r\n<strong>80/20</strong>\r\n\r\nIt all comes back to the critical few. In the book, The 80/20 Principle, the first key principle is \"A minority of inputs lead to a majority of outputs.\"','The Value of Focus, Unloading, and Why We Need Simplicity','','inherit','open','open','','3211-revision-v1','','','2016-01-01 04:49:27','2016-01-01 04:49:27','',3211,'http://shipordeliver.com/blog/2016/01/01/3211-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3215,1,'2016-01-01 05:02:02','2016-01-01 05:02:02','I need things to be simple to stay sane.\r\n\r\nSince the end of my insane semester, I\'ve had a lot of time to do what I love doing the most-- thinking, reading, and observing the world around me through literature, the arts, and entertainment. Due to my ambitious nature, I of course also subconsciously pick up cues and hints about success, and try to find general trends in the traits of people who have created a grand life for themselves. Even while I\'m supposed to be relaxing. (A separate post on my neurotic s