n almost compulsive manner. Look no further than the design of Apple products, with the iPads and iPhones displaying only a screen and a button.\r\n\r\nWhere this compulsion comes from, I\'ll explore in a bit, but it is undeniably effective. Un-cluttering the mind and having one\'s eyes set on a specific goal makes it much easier to know what things to do to get there. The same intense focus is on display in other industry giants-- Bill Gates\'s Linkedin profile lists one (failed) degree and one company to which he devoted his life to. Musk built up Zip2, Paypal, and SpaceX, but he did it one at a time. In <em>Lean In,</em> Sheryl Sandberg talks about her career path, and it is clear she never concentrated on anything but one job, or one degree, at a time.\r\n\r\nOne of my greatest weaknesses is trying to take on too much at once. The past semester, I was working full time while taking 3 graduate level classes, and starting side projects for fun. The thing is, while I may have <em>survived</em> the semester, I did not necessarily accomplish anything I was particularly proud of at either work, school, project, or relationship-wise, aside from the juggling itself.\r\n\r\nWhat I\'ve found is that this is a millennial tendency. One of my roommates is simultaneously planning out the next steps in his career while starting a small fund on the side. A bunch of coworkers are doing multiple \"side projects\" and taking MOOCs on the side to enhance their careers. I don\'t know a single software engineer who isn\'t trying to learn a new skill or working on their own pet project after work. Of course, there is also no denial that job hunting is more prevalent than ever-- and while it is becoming more acceptable in our industry, I\'m not sure many of my colleagues are doing it for the right reason.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Maximization: a Questionable Effort</b>\r\n\r\nIf you saw one of my colleague\'s Linkedin profiles, you\'d be shocked at how many random certifications she has, random things that she\'s learning on the side (coding, marketing, etc.), MOOCs she\'s auditing, random side projects and internships she\'s doing, etc. In fact, I know dozens of people who have similar resumes and profiles, and they are sure to be leaving out things to keep it to a respectable length! It all seems very impressive at first glance, until you start to wonder a few things.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>What does this person do for fun? If I (as a potential hiring manager or future coworker) am going to be spending the majority of my working day with this person, will it actually be an enjoyable experience?</li>\r\n	<li>Will he or she actually do a good job? If they are given the opportunity to work somewhere, and are immediately thinking of the next job or step, how can you have any confidence they\'ll deliver value?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Do We Really Need This?</b>\r\n\r\nAside from the questionable productivity of \"maximizers\", one can also find a ton of holes in their assumptions. They are as follows:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Breadth (a lot of things) is better than depth (going into one thing deeply)</li>\r\n	<li>People are more impressed by quantity over quality</li>\r\n	<li>It\'s important to plan ahead and mitigate risk</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe question I raise is whether any of that\'s really necessary. Let\'s take careers: sure, people looking to move up absolutely need to cultivate their skills-- by why not take a more direct route? As an example, a favorite quote of mine is from productivity/life-hacking guru Tim Ferriss:\r\n<blockquote>“It is far more lucrative and fun to leverage your strengths instead of attempting to fix all the chinks in your armor. The choice is between multiplication of results using strengths or incremental improvement fixing weaknesses that will, at best, become mediocre. Focus on better use of your best weapons instead of constant repair.”</blockquote>\r\nHow does focusing on strengths relate to focus? Well, knowing where you are strong helps you direct your energies appropriately. A friend of mine wants to become a Product Manager at a software company. He is currently in an entry-level service role at a startup. I asked him how he planned to go about getting into a PM role. He responded the way many aspiring careerists do: \"Well, I don\'t have a technology or hard science background, so I\'m going to take some courses or maybe get a degree in Computer Science. Then, to establish credibility with the engineers that I\'ll be working with, I plan to work as a software engineer for 2-3 years and familiarize myself well with product and engineering at a tech company. After that, I\'ll start applying to Product roles.\"\r\n\r\nIronically, his strengths already play well to Product Management: he is a great communicator, naturally a strategic thinker, and has a great eye for design. He is certainly not wrong that he would benefit from the technical training and from work experience with engineers, but the larger question is ignored-- why not just apply directly to product management positions now? There is no greater substitute than real world experience, and working so hard to get a little bit better technically only provides marginal benefits at best. (Of course, this changes if the PM role required greater technical training-- e.g. at Google, Quora, etc. where it is crucial, but for the majority of PM roles he\'d be fine applying today.)\r\n\r\nWhen I was preparing for the LSAT for law school applications, I was pretty active on a bunch of LSAT forums and in study groups. People would routinely ask what the best publications to read were to improve their vocabulary, whether sudoku helped with logic games, and sometimes even which law school had the most attractive student body. Interestingly enough, the highest scorers could probably attribute 80-90% of their scores to plowing through practice tests and learning from their mistakes each time.\r\n\r\nEven in other facets of life, like interior decorating, people are constantly adding the non-essential. Perhaps the visual  impact of buying a new TV, closet, door replacement, couch replacement, and rug could be achieved by removing clutter and painting the walls to better achieve color coordination.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>It\'s Really Just the 80/20</strong>\r\n\r\nIt all comes back to the critical few. In the book, The 80/20 Principle, the first key principle is \"A minority of inputs lead to a majority of outputs.\"\r\n\r\nConversely, a MAJORITY of inputs lead to a MINORITY of outputs.\r\n\r\nSo re-examine life and see if you are investing in the right things. For myself personally, I\'ve been juggling ideas of where I wanted to be 5 years from now, and this confusion led me to take on several side projects and getting my feet wet with an array of random new skills to \"prepare.\" I now know that this was deterring myself from being GREAT at what I do now: being a Project Manager and a CS student. The rest can be categorized as hobbies or interests, but I will be sure they will not take up more than 20% of my time.\r\n\r\nHow can you apply focus and the 80/20 rule in your life?','The Value of Focus, Unloading, and Why We Need Simplicity','','inherit','open','open','','3211-revision-v1','','','2016-01-01 16:38:47','2016-01-01 16:38:47','',3211,'http://shipordeliver.com/blog/2016/01/01/3211-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(3219,1,'2016-01-01 16:49:59','2016-01-01 16:49:59','I recently read <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1490313370/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=9325&creativeASIN=1490313370&linkCode=as2&tag=shipor-20&linkId=JZMMBBPJ4CVK7UYR\">Choose Yourself!</a><img src=\"http://ir-na.amazon-adsystem.com/e/ir?t=shipor-20&l=as2&o=1&a=1490313370\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" border=\"0\" alt=\"\" style=\"border:none !important; margin:0px !important;\" /> by James Altucher and think he has some unique ideas. One of them is to become an \"idea machine\", whereby 